We modelled the increasing whole-brain radioactivity signal related to radiotracer uptake across the PET scan period. For each participant, we assume an underlying baseline activity (Ybase) when no task was performed to model the radiotracer uptake. We subtracted Ybase from the time-series data to obtain baseline-corrected data:
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$$\begin{eqnarray*}
{{\rm{Y}}_{{\rm{basecorr}}}} = {\rm{Y}} - {{\rm{Y}}_{{\rm{base}}}}
\end{eqnarray*}
$$\end{document}where Ybase is the underlying baseline time series for each voxel.

Then, we can estimate βtask as
\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym}
\usepackage{amsfonts}
\usepackage{amssymb}
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$$\begin{eqnarray*}
{\rm Y}_{\rm basecorr} = {\beta_{\rm task\,\cdot regressor_{\rm task}}} + {\rm \varepsilon }.
\end{eqnarray*}
$$\end{document}

In another GLM, we approximate the baseline using grey matter mean (regressorGM) as confound:
